DataElement.preferredDefinition: The identification number of a tooth with dentin hypersensitivity present

DataElementConcept.preferredDefinition: the presence of dentin hypersensitivity on a tooth

ObjectClass.preferredDefinition: is an organ, the organ parts of which primarily consist of dentine and dental enamel; together with other teeth it constitutes a subdivision of the facial skeleton. Example(s): incisor, molar.

Concepts.definition: The hard bonelike structures in the jaws of vertebrates; primarily used for eating.

Property.preferredDefinition: The hard portion of the tooth surrounding the pulp, covered by enamel on the crown and cementum on the root. Dentin is harder and denser than bone but softer than enamel.:A local or general reaction of an organism following contact with a specific allergen to which it has been previously exposed and to which it has become sensitized.:Being or existing in a specified place or at the specified time.

Concepts.definition: The hard portion of the tooth surrounding the pulp, covered by enamel on the crown and cementum on the root. Dentin is harder and denser than bone but softer than enamel.
An immune response that occurs following exposure to an innocuous antigen, but that does not require the presence of preformed antibodies to the antigen.
Being or existing in a specified place or at the specified time.

ConceptualDomain.preferredDefinition: evaluations of the patient and the patient's disease.

RepresentationTerm.preferredDefinition: The teeth collectively in the dental arch. Dentition ordinarily refers to the natural teeth in position in their alveoli. Dentition referring to the deciduous teeth is DENTITION, PRIMARY; to the permanent teeth, DENTITION, PERMANENT. (From Jablonski, Dictionary of Dentistry, 1992):A system of numbered categories for representation of data.
